<subSubSection id="CE8DB8D8FFFDA13565CFFF00BDAB0C00" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" type="description">
<paragraph id="8628EB53FFFDA13565CFFF00B97808A9" blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1301]" box="[199,1385,151,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">
<emphasis id="B4E33741FFFDA13565CFFF00BD4808A9" bold="true" box="[199,345,151,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">Description.</emphasis>
Male. 
<emphasis id="B4E33741FFFDA13564AFFF00BE3808A9" box="[423,553,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">Coloration.</emphasis>
Body dark, with distal halves of tibiae and tarsomeres 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA1356199FF0FB8AD08A9" box="[1169,1212,152,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="2.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="1.0">1–4</number>
paler (
<figureCitation id="1EACF7D6FFFDA1356002FF00B95B08A9" box="[1290,1354,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1937,1959]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,554,1915]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,554,1915]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Brachypogon freidbergi sp. nov., holotype male: a. wing; b. radial cells of wing; c. hind leg; d. tibial comb, spur and palisade setae of hind leg; e. two distal tarsomeres of hind leg." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227558/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">
Fig. 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA1356036FF0FB95B08A9" box="[1342,1354,152,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
c).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8628EB53FFFDA13565CFFF2BB84F0926" blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1301]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">
<emphasis id="B4E33741FFFDA13565CFFF2BBD1508CC" box="[199,260,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">Head</emphasis>
. Eyes pubescent, widely separated. Antenna with 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA135667DFF2BBF8008CD" box="[885,913,188,212]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="13.0">13</number>
flagellomeres, plume well-developed; total flagellum length 
<quantity id="416F46B6FFFDA1356461FF77BDCB08EE" box="[361,474,224,248]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.4" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" unit="mm" value="0.44">0.44 mm</quantity>
; flagellomere 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA1356784FF77BE8B08E1" box="[652,666,224,248]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="1.0">1</number>
with two whorls of long setae and two sensilla coeloconica; flagellomeres 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA1356430FE93BD7E0905" box="[312,367,260,284]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="6.5" valueMax="11.0" valueMin="2.0">2–11</number>
fused, but with well defined anterior and posterior margins. Third palpal segment with small apical sensory pit; length 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA13564BEFEB0BDC30959" box="[438,466,295,320]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="46.0">46</number>
Μm, PR 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA135673DFEBFBE7B0959" box="[565,618,296,320]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="2.42">2.42</number>
. Fourth palpal segment bearing 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA13566D9FEBFBFCE0959" box="[977,991,296,320]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="2.0">2</number>
long setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8628EB53FFFDA13565CFFEDBB9980A93" blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1301]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">
<emphasis id="B4E33741FFFDA13565CFFEDBBD09097C" box="[199,280,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">Thorax</emphasis>
. Katepisternum with single seta; anepisternum bare. Transverse suture on scutum well-developed, 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA1356086FEDBB98D097D" box="[1422,1436,332,356]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="1.0">1</number>
anterior and 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA1356420FEF8BD270991" box="[296,310,367,392]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="5.0">5</number>
posterior supraalar setae present. Scutellum with 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA135667AFEE7BF910991" box="[882,896,368,392]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="4.0">4</number>
large setae. Wing (
<figureCitation id="1EACF7D6FFFDA1356168FEF8B8B00991" box="[1120,1185,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1937,1959]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,554,1915]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,554,1915]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Brachypogon freidbergi sp. nov., holotype male: a. wing; b. radial cells of wing; c. hind leg; d. tibial comb, spur and palisade setae of hind leg; e. two distal tarsomeres of hind leg." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227558/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">
Fig. 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA135619EFEE7B8B00991" box="[1174,1185,368,392]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
a) membrane hyaline, lacking macrotrichia; two very small radial cells present (
<figureCitation id="1EACF7D6FFFDA135664CFE03BF9809B4" box="[836,905,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1937,1959]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,554,1915]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,554,1915]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Brachypogon freidbergi sp. nov., holotype male: a. wing; b. radial cells of wing; c. hind leg; d. tibial comb, spur and palisade setae of hind leg; e. two distal tarsomeres of hind leg." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227558/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">
Fig. 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA1356676FE03BF9809B4" box="[894,905,404,429]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
b), r 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA13566B7FE34BFD609A8" box="[959,967,419,433]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="1.0">1</number>
slit-like, r 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA135614DFE34B85C09A8" box="[1093,1101,419,433]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="2.0">2</number>
narrow; wing veins slightly infuscated, darkest on well-defined stigma; vein M 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA13567D5FE5EBEF409CE" box="[733,741,457,471]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="2.0">2</number>
absent; Cu 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA135666FFE5EBF7E09CE" box="[871,879,457,471]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="1.0">1</number>
, Cu 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA13566A8FE5EBFB909CE" box="[928,936,457,471]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="2.0">2</number>
obsolete on distal halves; wing length 
<quantity id="416F46B6FFFDA1356063FE2DBCD709E0" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" unit="mm" value="0.75">0.75 mm</quantity>
; CR 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA1356409FE76BD2709E3" box="[257,310,481,506]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="0.5">0.50</number>
. Femora and tibiae of mid legs slender, those of fore and hind (
<figureCitation id="1EACF7D6FFFDA1356104FE76B85C09E3" box="[1036,1101,481,506]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1937,1959]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,554,1915]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,554,1915]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Brachypogon freidbergi sp. nov., holotype male: a. wing; b. radial cells of wing; c. hind leg; d. tibial comb, spur and palisade setae of hind leg; e. two distal tarsomeres of hind leg." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227558/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">
Fig. 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA135614AFE75B85C09E3" box="[1090,1101,482,506]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
c) legs slightly broader. 
<collectingCountry id="FE80ABC3FFFDA135606CFE76B98D09E3" box="[1380,1436,481,506]" name="India" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">Hind</collectingCountry>
tibia with comb composed of 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA13564E1FD92BDE60A07" box="[489,503,517,542]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="6.0">6</number>
large setae, slender and moderately long apical spur, and basitarsus bearing single row of dense palisade setae (
<figureCitation id="1EACF7D6FFFDA13564DEFDBEBE040A5B" box="[470,533,553,578]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1937,1959]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,554,1915]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,554,1915]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Brachypogon freidbergi sp. nov., holotype male: a. wing; b. radial cells of wing; c. hind leg; d. tibial comb, spur and palisade setae of hind leg; e. two distal tarsomeres of hind leg." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227558/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">
Fig. 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA1356702FDBEBE040A5B" box="[522,533,553,578]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
d). Tarsomere 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA13567B1FDBDBED60A5B" box="[697,711,554,578]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="4.0">4</number>
(
<figureCitation id="1EACF7D6FFFDA13567DDFDBEBF050A5B" box="[725,788,553,578]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1937,1959]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,554,1915]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,554,1915]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Brachypogon freidbergi sp. nov., holotype male: a. wing; b. radial cells of wing; c. hind leg; d. tibial comb, spur and palisade setae of hind leg; e. two distal tarsomeres of hind leg." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227558/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">
Fig. 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA1356601FDBDBF050A5B" box="[777,788,554,578]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
e) subcylindrical, bearing 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA1356132FDBDB8750A5B" box="[1082,1124,554,578]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2</number>
long apical sinuous sensilla capitata; tarsomere 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA135647BFDDABD900A7F" box="[371,385,589,614]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="5.0">5</number>
of all legs with small, equal-sized claws, lacking inner teeth, each with single long basal seta at base and with bifid apex; slender empodia present. Fore, mid and hind tarsal ratios: 
<collectingCountry id="FE80ABC3FFFDA1356155FDE5B8900A90" box="[1117,1153,626,649]" name="Chile" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">TR</collectingCountry>
I 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA1356185FDE5B8A30A93" box="[1165,1202,626,650]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="1.7">1.7</number>
, 
<collectingCountry id="FE80ABC3FFFDA13561B6FDE5B8F30A90" box="[1214,1250,626,649]" name="Chile" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">TR</collectingCountry>
II 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA13561FBFDE6B9090A93" box="[1267,1304,625,650]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="1.6">1.6</number>
, 
<collectingCountry id="FE80ABC3FFFDA135602CFDE5B9590A90" box="[1316,1352,626,649]" name="Chile" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">TR</collectingCountry>
III 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA1356056FDE5B9950A93" box="[1374,1412,626,650]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="2.1">2.1</number>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8628EB53FFFDA13565CFFD0FBD230BB4" blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1301]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">
<emphasis id="B4E33741FFFDA13565CFFD0FBD200AA8" box="[199,305,664,689]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">Genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="1EACF7D6FFFDA135644AFD0FBD980AA8" box="[322,393,664,689]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,249,1914,1936]" captionTargetBox="[219,1368,202,1888]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[211,1376,193,1893]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Brachypogon freidbergi sp. nov., holotype male: a. male genitalia in ventral view, b. gonostylus, c. parameres, d. aedeagus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227559/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">
Fig. 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA1356471FD0EBD980AA8" box="[377,393,665,689]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
a). Tergite 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA135670DFD0EBE020AA8" box="[517,531,665,689]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="9.0">9</number>
tapering abruptly distally, with pair of slender elongate apicolateral processes, each bearing single subapical seta; ventrodistal portion with large, heavily sclerotized, semicircular proctiger. Sternite 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA13565FDFD76BD120AE0" box="[245,259,737,761]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="9.0">9</number>
moderately short, about 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA1356715FD77BE510AE0" box="[541,576,736,761]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="2.5">2.5</number>
times broader than long, posterior margin nearly straight. Gonocoxite stout, broadest near base. Gonostylus (
<figureCitation id="1EACF7D6FFFDA135670DFC93BE560B04" box="[517,583,772,797]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,249,1914,1936]" captionTargetBox="[219,1368,202,1888]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[211,1376,193,1893]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Brachypogon freidbergi sp. nov., holotype male: a. male genitalia in ventral view, b. gonostylus, c. parameres, d. aedeagus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227559/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">
Fig. 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA1356731FC93BE560B04" box="[569,583,772,797]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
b) short, broad, deeply bifurcate, Y-shaped; both branches of similar length, pointed apically, inner branch bearing several long setae. Parameres (
<figureCitation id="1EACF7D6FFFDA1356695FCBFBFF00B58" box="[925,993,808,833]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,249,1914,1936]" captionTargetBox="[219,1368,202,1888]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[211,1376,193,1893]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Brachypogon freidbergi sp. nov., holotype male: a. male genitalia in ventral view, b. gonostylus, c. parameres, d. aedeagus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227559/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">
Fig. 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA13566DAFCBEBFF00B58" box="[978,993,809,833]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
c) fused, slightly shorter than aedeagus; basal apodemes, lateral margins and apex well sclerotized, mid portion more lightly sclerotized; apex bifid, each half with pointed tip. Aedeagus stout, with low basal arch and bilobed apex, well sclerotized, especially in basal half (
<figureCitation id="1EACF7D6FFFDA13565DAFC03BD040BB4" box="[210,277,916,941]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,249,1914,1936]" captionTargetBox="[219,1368,202,1888]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[211,1376,193,1893]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Brachypogon freidbergi sp. nov., holotype male: a. male genitalia in ventral view, b. gonostylus, c. parameres, d. aedeagus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/227559/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">
Fig. 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA135640EFC03BD040BB4" box="[262,277,916,941]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
d).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8628EB53FFFDA13565CFFC2FBE4F0BC8" blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1301]" box="[199,606,952,977]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">
<emphasis id="B4E33741FFFDA13565CFFC2FBDF00BC8" bold="true" box="[199,481,952,977]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">Female and immatures.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8628EB53FFFDA13565CFFC4BBDAB0C00" blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1301]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">
<emphasis id="B4E33741FFFDA13565CFFC4BBDF10BEC" bold="true" box="[199,480,988,1013]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">Derivation of the name.</emphasis>
This species is named after Amnon Freidberg, who kindly loaned us the collection of biting midges from 
<collectingCountry id="FE80ABC3FFFDA135647CFB97BDA70C00" box="[372,438,1024,1049]" name="Israel" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">Israel</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CE8DB8D8FFFDA13565CFFBB3BCFE0D0C" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8628EB53FFFDA13565CFFBB3BCFE0D0C" blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1301]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">
<emphasis id="B4E33741FFFDA13565CFFBB3BD2A0C24" bold="true" box="[199,315,1060,1085]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">Remarks.</emphasis>
The unusual, deeply bifurcate, Y-shaped gonostylus and the long finger-like apicolateral processes in male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName id="419790D0FFFDA1356476FBDFBE9D0C78" box="[382,652,1096,1121]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Brachypogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="freidbergi">
<emphasis id="B4E33741FFFDA1356476FBDFBE9D0C78" box="[382,652,1096,1121]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">Brachypogon freidbergi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are unique among all other extant species of the subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="419790D0FFFDA135603EFBDFB9840C78" box="[1334,1429,1096,1121]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Isohelea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B4E33741FFFDA135603EFBDFB9840C78" box="[1334,1429,1096,1121]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">Isohelea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The latter character is found only in 
<taxonomicName id="419790D0FFFDA1356738FBFABF9F0C9C" authority="Meunier, 1904" authorityName="Meunier" authorityYear="1904" box="[560,910,1132,1157]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Brachypogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prominulus">
<emphasis id="B4E33741FFFDA1356738FBFABE500C9D" box="[560,577,1133,1156]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B4E33741FFFDA1356758FBFBBEDF0C9C" box="[592,718,1132,1157]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">prominulus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="E20696A2FFFDA13567D5FBFBBF970C9C" author="Meunier" box="[733,902,1132,1157]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" refString="Meunier, F. (1904) Monographie des Cecidomyidae, des Sciaridae, des Mycetophilidae et des Chironomidae de l'ambre de la Baltique (concl.). Annales de la Societe Scientifique de Bruxelles (Mem.), 28, 93 - 275." type="journal article" year="1904">
Meunier, 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA1356643FBFABF970C9C" box="[843,902,1133,1157]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="1904.0">1904</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, the species known from Eocene Baltic amber. The shape of the aedeagus and the sclerotized ventrodistal region of tergite 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA135610DFB06B8020CB0" box="[1029,1043,1169,1193]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="9.0">9</number>
of this new species are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName id="419790D0FFFDA13565F4FB22BE930CD4" authority="Spinelli &amp; Grogan, 1994" authorityName="Spinelli &amp; Grogan" authorityYear="1994" box="[252,642,1204,1229]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Brachypogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hugoi">
<emphasis id="B4E33741FFFDA13565F4FB22BD4C0CD4" box="[252,349,1204,1229]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">B. hugoi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="E20696A2FFFDA135646EFB23BE930CD4" author="Spinelli" box="[358,642,1204,1229]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" refString="Spinelli, G. R. &amp; Grogan, W. L. (1994) Two new Neotropical species of the subgenus Isohelea of Brachypogon, with the description of the female of B. (I.) misionensis and a key to the Neotropical species (Diptera: Ceratopogonidae). Revista de la Sociedad Entomologica Argentina, 53, 1 - 8." type="journal article" year="1994">
Spinelli &amp; Grogan, 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA1356742FB22BE930CD4" box="[586,642,1205,1229]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="1994.0">1994</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from the Neotropics. Similar parameres, which are completely fused basally and divided in apical half, are known in 
<taxonomicName id="419790D0FFFDA13567A7FB4EB83B0CE8" authority="Goetghebuer, 1920" authorityName="Goetghebuer" authorityYear="1920" box="[687,1066,1240,1265]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Brachypogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sociabilis">
<emphasis id="B4E33741FFFDA13567A7FB4EBED10CE9" box="[687,704,1241,1264]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B4E33741FFFDA13567C6FB4FBF280CE8" box="[718,825,1240,1265]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">sociabilis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="E20696A2FFFDA1356640FB4FB8320CE8" author="Goetghebuer" box="[840,1059,1240,1265]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" refString="Goetghebuer, M. (1920) Ceratopogoninae de Belgique. Memoires du Musee Royal d'Histoire Naturelle de Belgique, 8 (3), 1 - 116. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 10099" type="journal article" year="1920">
Goetghebuer, 
<number id="305FF974FFFDA13566EFFB4EB8320CE8" box="[999,1059,1241,1265]" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" value="1920.0">1920</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, the widely distributed European species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
